# Copy to .sandcastle/.env (plaintext) or .env.sandcastle (for dotenvx) and fill in.
#
# Recommended: encrypt this file with the standalone dotenvx binary and commit the
# ciphertext, then decrypt at runtime with DOTENV_PRIVATE_KEY (no secrets in git):
#   dotenvx encrypt -f .env.sandcastle
#   DOTENV_PRIVATE_KEY=... sandcastle run --repo /path/to/target-repo

# --- pi coding agent ---------------------------------------------------------
# Pi uses OAuth (ChatGPT/Codex) persisted under .sandcastle/pi; no key needed if
# you authenticate interactively once. Set provider keys here if your model needs them.
# OPENAI_API_KEY=

# --- git identity for agent commits -----------------------------------------
SANDCASTLE_GIT_USER_NAME=Sandcastle Bot
SANDCASTLE_GIT_USER_EMAIL=sandcastle@example.com

# --- GitHub (for `gh` inside the sandbox) ------------------------------------
# Token used by the planner (`gh issue list`) and the merge phase (`git push` +
# `gh pr create`). A fine-grained PAT must grant these repository permissions on the
# target repo (a classic PAT needs the `repo` scope):
#   - Contents:      Read and write   (git push)
#   - Pull requests: Read and write   (gh pr create)
#   - Issues:        Read and write   (planner/merge read & comment on issues)
#   - Metadata:      Read-only        (required, granted automatically)
# Without Contents+PRs write you'll see "403 Permission denied" / "Resource not
# accessible by personal access token" and no PR is opened.
# GH_TOKEN=
